<br>
Jeff said:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The Lutherans and Anglicans both believe that the Eucharist is the Body and Blood of Our Lord.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You then replied:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Is this true about Anglicans? My theology textbook indicates otherwise, but I haven't taken time to pursue the matter.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Essentially it is true, but there are some differences.<br>
<br>
Roman Catholics believe in transubstantiation, which is defined as this:<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;According to this position, the substance, or inner reality, of the bread and wine are changed into the substance of the body and blood of Christ, but the accidents, or external qualities known through the senses (color, weight, taste), remain unchanged.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The above is from Charles W Ranson from mb-soft.com/believe website.<br>
<br>
Luthernas and Anglicans believe in consubstantiation, which is defined as this:<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Consubstantiation rests on the same philosophical assumptions as the medieval doctrine of transubstantiation, which it opposed. Both doctrines depend on Aristotle's teaching that matter consists of accidents, which can be perceived by the senses, and substance, which the mind grasps and which constitutes essential reality. Both agree that, in the Eucharist, the accidents of the bread and wine remain unchanged. Unlike the doctrine of transubstantiation, however, that of consubstantiation asserts that the substance of the bread and wine is also unchanged, the ubiquitous body of Christ coexisting &quot;in, with, and under&quot; the substance of the bread, and the blood of Christ in, with, and under the wine, by the power of the Word of God.<br>
<br>
Luther illustrated consubstantiation by the analogy of iron put into fire: Iron and fire are united in red-hot iron; yet the two substances remain unchanged.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The above is by Charles P. Price from mb-soft.com/believe webiste.<br>
<br>
I know that Orthodoxy holds to the real presence of Christ in the Eucharist, but does not accept the terminology of Rome, that is transubstantiation.  Yet they also don't claim consubstantiation either, from what I can tell.  Jeff, you can correct me here if I'm wrong.<br>
<br>
Anway, as can be seen, Roman Catholics, Orthodox, and the very earliest Protestant churches (Lutheran and Anglican), hold to some degree the presence of our Lord in the Eucharist.  It is not just a symbolic gesture done in remembrance, it is a very meaningful sacrament.<br>
<br>
I don't say that to be condescending, but it is worthwhile to know that a large portion of Christendom accepts this doctrine and it can be traced back to the ECF who saw this as truth.  They took John 6 to be literally such.  There is scriptural, historical and traditional reasons to accept this doctrine.<br>
<br>
I will also admit that it is one of the largest stumbling blocks to Christian unity, almost as severe as debates on the doctrines of Grace.<br>
<br>
In a final note to Brian.  I can understand why you might be starting to feel uncomfortable taking communion in a church that only considers it to be symbolic.  I attend a non-denominational Christian church with my wife, who is VERY protestant.  While she isn't quite sure that communion is only symbolic, she isn't to your point yet.  Anyway, even though the Roman Catholic church states that I am not to take communion outside, I have.  I'm not sure what happens though.  I still take it in full reverence, and I am willing to take it as bread and wine only as an act of unity with Christian brothers and sisters.  However, I can't deny the possibility that the mystery takes place because of my faith.  If it does, it does.<br>
<br>
I'm probably saying all that very inadequately.   I hope I haven't confused this discussion.<br>
 <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
<br>
