<br>
When I was starting to delve into this issue, I too used the &quot;metaphor&quot; argument. But two problems with that were quickly presented to me:<br>
<br>
1. many disciples left him over this: if it were merely a metaphor, then we are left with the conclusion that Christ let his own disciples leave him, when all he had to do is tell them he was using a metaphor. In other words, if he was using a metaphor, he knew *his own disciples* took it literally, denied them the truth, and parted company with them. Why would he not simply correct their misunderstanding or explain himself further, as he did with every other metaphor he uses in the Gospels? Instead, he repeated himself, then asked the Apostles if they were going to leave him over this hard saying as well. They replied &quot;Lord, to whom shall we go? thou hast the words of eternal life.&quot; Hard words, yes, but they realized they would accept his words simply because of who he is. Powerful stuff. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
2. Eating flesh and drinking blood *is* a metaphor already in scripture - but in a completely *negative* sense. Someone recently pointed out to me: &quot;The phrase &quot;to eat the flesh and drink the blood,&quot; when used figuratively among the Jews, as among the Arabs of today, meant to inflict upon a person some serious injury, especially by calumny or by false accusation. To interpret the phrase figuratively then would be to make our Lord promise life everlasting to the culprit for slandering and hating him, which would reduce the whole passage to utter nonsense. For an examples of this use, refer to Micah 3:3; 2 Samuel 23:15-17; Revelation 17:6; Isaiah 49:26, 9:18-20.&quot;<br>
<br>
In other words, even though the metaphor view makes more sense when we have our Protestant glasses on, it actually creates more problems than it &quot;fixes&quot;, does it not?<br>
<br>
About John 6:55, what I meant is that Christ, who had the opportunity of saying &quot;For my flesh is symbolic meat, and my blood is symbolic drink&quot;, instead said &quot;For my flesh is REAL meat, and my blood is REAL drink.&quot; He knows how his listeners are understanding his words up to this point, and instead of saying &quot;I'm just being symbolic&quot;, he hammers the literalness of his words home. The Greek word here is for the sole purpose of emphasizing something is literal, and NOT symbolic.<br>
<br>
Besides the scriptural issues, I am also bothered by the fact that by taking the &quot;symbolic&quot; view, I am on the opposite side of the fence on this issue from all of church history, all the way back and including the early church fathers, some of who had direct communication with the apostles. Now, like Eugene, I'm not ready to put them on the same level of authority as scripture, but it sure puts some perspective on the issue. Especially since I trust the &quot;authority&quot; of these same men to determine canonicity for us, etc, which I think was Jeff's earlier point.<br>
<br>
Esdras, your comments early in this thread about Christ being metaphorical only at the last supper (because he hadn't made the sacrifice on the cross yet) is very interesting - is this the common Catholic view, or just your personal view? Jeff, does the Orthodox church have the same view of this instance?<br>
<br>
Brian <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esdras>esdras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator<br>Sir Esdras, Brewmeister <br>of the Great White North</span><br>  Posts: 195<br> <font color=#B87333>(6/27/03 3:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=22>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www3.sympatico.ca/gsmorgan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Eucharist</span><hr size=1> Hi Brian:<br>
<br>
Actually, I'm not sure what the &quot;official&quot; view is regarding those scripture passages.  My thought on that came about while discussing the topic with my wife.<br>
<br>
We looked up the passages in Strong's and it was pretty clear that Christ was saying (to paraphrase) &quot;this is, as it were, my body...&quot;<br>
<br>
Of course, my wife said that Christ was speaking metaphorically, and I had to agree, but that is when I said that it made logical sense since He hadn't been crucified yet.  Admittedly, it would have been easier had He said something like, this will transform and/or be instilled with my body when you gather after I have been put to death, or something like that.<br>
<br>
So, I had to look at the scripture for what it said.  Although I firmly avow God being all powerful, and without getting too far off topic here, outside of our concept of linear time (there is some scripture to support this), Jesus was MAN while on earth and therefore - I believe - subject to linear time.  Christ's physical, bodily sacrifice had not yet taken place, therefore the bread and wine at the last supper could not contain the presense of His sacrifice.  While I don't think that this is outside of God's ability, I feel that it is logically consistent.<br>
<br>
So I guess I can say that it is my personal view, but one that I think makes sense when you consider the words spoken at the last supper.  It is also why I feel you must take those verses in conjunction with the verses from John 6 to get a real understanding of the Eucharistic sacrament.<br>
<br>
By the way, I liked your post above.  I'll have to remember what you said the next time my wife and I discuss this topic.  Who knows, she might take that next step to where you are at the moment.<br>
<br>
Thanks!<br>
<br>
God bless,<br>
esdras <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
